WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.980
Hi, thanks everyone.

00:00:02.980 --> 00:00:06.340
So I'm a data scientist at Bristol-Myers Squibb,

00:00:06.340 --> 00:00:07.820
and I'm here to talk about a framework

00:00:07.820 --> 00:00:10.780
for reproducible and collaborative data wrangling.

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:14.860
But first, I'd like to ask if you've ever heard

00:00:14.860 --> 00:00:17.740
of type one versus type two fun.

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:20.879
If you haven't, type one fun is an activity

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:22.500
that's enjoyable while it's happening.

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:26.420
So this could be sitting on a sunny beach on vacation.

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:27.980
Type two fun, on the other hand,

00:00:27.980 --> 00:00:30.860
is an activity that's not as enjoyable

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:31.700
while it's happening.

00:00:31.700 --> 00:00:33.060
You might even be miserable.

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:35.459
But then, when the activity is over,

00:00:35.459 --> 00:00:37.660
you look back on it fondly.

00:00:37.660 --> 00:00:40.060
And so, classic examples of type two fun

00:00:40.060 --> 00:00:43.619
include exercise, or my personal favorite,

00:00:43.619 --> 00:00:46.439
jumping into an icy alpine lake.

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:48.720
And so, today I'll talk to you about how,

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:51.180
just like type two fun, taking the plunge

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:53.419
into reproducible research is worth it.

00:00:55.599 --> 00:00:57.939
So I often think about reproducible research

00:00:58.779 --> 00:01:02.099
in the context of ad hoc analysis requests.

00:01:02.099 --> 00:01:03.900
I work with a lot of clinical trial data

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:07.779
in a large organization, and I might get a request

00:01:07.779 --> 00:01:09.500
from an investigator such as this one.

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:12.900
So maybe they ask me to look at baseline albumin levels

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:15.500
across two different clinical trials.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:18.139
And albumin is a relatively common lab measurement,

00:01:18.139 --> 00:01:20.580
so I'll say, okay, I'll take a look.

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:23.120
But then, when I actually start looking into the data,

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:25.739
I realize that there's a whole bunch of questions

00:01:25.739 --> 00:01:28.379
that I'll need to answer in order to actually go back

00:01:28.379 --> 00:01:30.699
to the investigator with the solution.

00:01:30.699 --> 00:01:33.940
So maybe I need to figure out which specimen type

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:37.400
I'm interested in, or maybe there's different units used,

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:40.180
so I need to perform a unit conversion step.

00:01:40.180 --> 00:01:42.980
And inevitably, most of the work goes into

00:01:42.980 --> 00:01:46.580
finding, cleaning, and structuring the data.

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:50.980
And this is really the classic 80-20 rule of data science,

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:55.059
where most of the work goes into this data wrangling step,

00:01:55.059 --> 00:01:57.779
and then you only have the last 20%

00:01:57.779 --> 00:01:59.239
where you do the actual analysis

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:02.699
and essentially get the answer.

00:02:02.699 --> 00:02:05.540
And oftentimes, or sometimes,

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:07.699
this can be disposable data work.

00:02:07.699 --> 00:02:09.380
You maybe just need to get to the answer

00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:11.220
as quickly as possible, and so you essentially

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:14.699
just turn in your homework and go on with your day.

00:02:14.699 --> 00:02:18.899
But I feel like fairly often, maybe you're asked

00:02:18.899 --> 00:02:21.300
to return to this analysis six months later,

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:24.779
or maybe you want to share your analysis with somebody else.

00:02:25.460 --> 00:02:27.660
And in this case, having disposable data work

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:30.500
isn't a really good solution here.

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:34.020
So one way to make this data wrangling more reusable

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:37.619
is to package it into a data product.

00:02:37.619 --> 00:02:40.179
And so what do I mean by a data product?

00:02:40.179 --> 00:02:45.100
In this case, a data product is an analysis-ready data set,

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:48.139
or a group of data sets that's versioned,

00:02:48.139 --> 00:02:50.660
reproducible, and shareable.

00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:53.020
And this is how you can essentially

00:02:53.020 --> 00:02:55.339
package your data wrangling work

00:02:55.339 --> 00:02:56.580
and collaborate with others

00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:58.699
on creating this data product object.

00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:03.100
The only small wrinkle here is that this is more work.

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:05.539
This is definitely the type two track here,

00:03:06.619 --> 00:03:08.339
but I'd like to talk through a framework

00:03:08.339 --> 00:03:09.979
for creating these data products

00:03:09.979 --> 00:03:12.300
and hope to convince you why it can be worth it

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:13.979
to create these data products.

00:03:15.179 --> 00:03:20.179
So at BMS, we've developed a suite of packages

00:03:20.979 --> 00:03:24.500
called DAPR, or data as a product in R,

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:26.259
that provides a framework for creating

00:03:26.259 --> 00:03:29.860
these reproducible data products.

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:32.259
These were developed by a group of us at BMS

00:03:32.259 --> 00:03:34.179
and are used across different types

00:03:34.179 --> 00:03:36.220
of scientific analysis questions,

00:03:36.220 --> 00:03:38.300
mostly in the exploratory space.

00:03:39.339 --> 00:03:42.500
The idea behind DAPR is that it allows multiple users

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:44.699
to pool their data wrangling efforts

00:03:44.699 --> 00:03:46.619
and then create this data product object

00:03:46.619 --> 00:03:48.059
that they can collaborate on.

00:03:49.059 --> 00:03:50.979
The overall goal is to be able to build

00:03:50.979 --> 00:03:53.059
these analysis-ready data products

00:03:53.059 --> 00:03:56.619
that follow sound data engineering principles.

00:03:56.619 --> 00:03:58.419
And so I'll talk through what I think

00:03:58.419 --> 00:04:00.220
is the core principle behind DAPR,

00:04:00.220 --> 00:04:02.259
and then I'll go through how you would actually use

00:04:02.259 --> 00:04:04.619
the DAPR framework to build a data product.

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:11.699
So the key principle behind DAPR is pretty simple.

00:04:11.699 --> 00:04:13.699
It's just to version all the things.

00:04:13.699 --> 00:04:16.220
So this comes in three different flavors.

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:18.940
You version your code, you version your environment,

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:20.820
and you version your data.

00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:24.100
I've arbitrarily ranked these by how hard I think they are,

00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:28.660
but DAPR attempts to make it easier for the user

00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:31.019
to do all these things and also forces them

00:04:31.019 --> 00:04:32.299
to version all of these things.

00:04:32.299 --> 00:04:35.739
So in terms of code, DAPR uses Git and GitHub,

00:04:35.739 --> 00:04:38.779
so users make sure to version control

00:04:38.779 --> 00:04:42.579
and commit and push their data wrangling code.

00:04:42.579 --> 00:04:44.420
In terms of versioning your environment,

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:48.739
it uses the renv package, so users track and install

00:04:48.739 --> 00:04:50.980
all their required package dependencies.

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:53.380
This is also very useful when you're sharing code

00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:55.380
with somebody else and you need them to start

00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:57.380
from the same point as you.

00:04:57.380 --> 00:04:59.779
And then in terms of versioning your data,

00:04:59.779 --> 00:05:02.899
DAPR tracks the metadata of all of the input files

00:05:02.899 --> 00:05:04.619
that you're using.

00:05:04.619 --> 00:05:07.059
And under the hood, it's using the pins package to do this.

00:05:07.059 --> 00:05:12.059
So this is a package that's, a wonderful package

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:14.899
that's used for publishing and sharing datasets.

00:05:14.899 --> 00:05:16.739
And one of the really nice things it does

00:05:16.739 --> 00:05:19.059
is it creates versioned datasets.

00:05:19.059 --> 00:05:21.540
And so DAPR uses this to track which versions

00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:23.700
of all of your input datasets you're using.

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:28.940
Okay, so that's the key principle behind DAPR,

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:30.100
but how does it actually work?

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:31.940
How do you build a data product?

00:05:33.179 --> 00:05:36.380
This is the DAPR workflow, and I'll build out these steps

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:37.380
as I walk through them.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:39.940
But the general idea is that you're going to start,

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:44.179
initialize your product, create an input data snapshot,

00:05:44.179 --> 00:05:48.299
do the actual building step where you add derivation code,

00:05:48.299 --> 00:05:50.500
then you do the version everything step,

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:53.859
and then finally you can deploy and share your data product.

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:57.700
So I'll jump into the first step here,

00:05:57.700 --> 00:06:01.059
which is how do you actually initialize a data product?

00:06:01.059 --> 00:06:04.500
So you'll need a few things in order to start.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:08.119
The first is you need to specify the remote board

00:06:08.119 --> 00:06:10.519
that will be used to store your data.

00:06:10.519 --> 00:06:12.079
This could be cloud storage,

00:06:12.079 --> 00:06:14.600
or a shared server, or a networked device.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:16.679
And you'll basically just need to gather the credentials

00:06:16.679 --> 00:06:18.239
or configuration details needed

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:20.440
to connect to this remote board.

00:06:21.679 --> 00:06:23.799
You can then use one DAPR command

00:06:23.799 --> 00:06:26.559
to initialize your local build environment.

00:06:26.559 --> 00:06:29.880
So this will initialize Git locally,

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:32.600
it will start RN for you

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:34.279
and track all your package dependencies,

00:06:34.279 --> 00:06:36.640
and it will save all the configuration details

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:38.679
you need to connect to your remote.

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:44.480
At this step, you can create an input data snapshot.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:47.760
So you would gather the input files that you need

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:49.660
that you're going to process.

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:52.399
In my world, this is a lot of clinical data sets,

00:06:52.399 --> 00:06:54.519
but this could be any type of input file

00:06:54.519 --> 00:06:57.359
as long as it's in rectangular format.

00:06:58.959 --> 00:07:01.940
DAPR then pins and syncs these input files

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:04.320
to your remote board and saves the versions

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:06.480
of all of the files that you're working with.

00:07:07.519 --> 00:07:11.559
Okay, we're now on the build step.

00:07:11.559 --> 00:07:13.959
So this is where you actually build the data product

00:07:13.959 --> 00:07:16.440
by adding derivation code.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:18.679
And there's quite a lot of flexibility here

00:07:18.679 --> 00:07:20.720
in how you approach this.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.119
DAPR provides essentially scaffolding code

00:07:23.119 --> 00:07:24.899
for how you might go about this,

00:07:24.899 --> 00:07:27.320
but often the way we approach this

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:30.079
is to create derivation functions

00:07:30.079 --> 00:07:31.799
where each function creates a data set

00:07:31.799 --> 00:07:33.959
that you might use for analysis.

00:07:33.959 --> 00:07:35.399
I'm showing an example here

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:38.519
where you have a deriveAlbumen function.

00:07:38.519 --> 00:07:41.320
And within the function, it will take a link

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:44.760
to the input data that's snapshotted on your remote board

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:46.359
and read that in and do all of the,

00:07:46.359 --> 00:07:48.160
essentially, data processing work.

00:07:49.679 --> 00:07:51.239
And each of these derivation functions

00:07:51.239 --> 00:07:53.200
might reference one or more input files,

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:55.880
and then you might have one or more derivation functions

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:57.959
that all build on top of each other.

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:00.880
And I should mention here

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:04.200
that we often use the targets package to help with this.

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:06.920
This is a really cool data pipeline package.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:07.959
It's kind of make-like,

00:08:07.959 --> 00:08:11.480
and it allows you to kind of set up all of your dependencies

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:13.519
in terms of the derivation functions.

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:17.839
So as I said before, there's quite a lot of flexibility

00:08:17.839 --> 00:08:20.239
in how you actually build your data product.

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:25.119
I'm showing here an example data product structure.

00:08:25.119 --> 00:08:26.880
So there's a lot going on here.

00:08:26.880 --> 00:08:28.880
The main thing I want you to focus on

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:31.399
is that the data product object itself

00:08:31.399 --> 00:08:33.200
is structured into three main pieces.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:36.640
So you have your inputs, your outputs, and your metadata.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.359
The inputs are all of your input files

00:08:39.359 --> 00:08:42.799
that are already synced to your remote board,

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:45.039
and then the outputs are all of the data sets

00:08:45.039 --> 00:08:48.200
that you've created from derivation functions.

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:50.159
And then you can optionally have metadata,

00:08:50.159 --> 00:08:51.760
such as a data dictionary,

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:55.280
to define what your column names are, for example.

00:08:56.960 --> 00:08:58.080
The other thing I'll note here

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:00.640
is that we attempt to make these data products

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:02.520
a little bit more lightweight

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:07.359
by having the inputs return links to the data themselves,

00:09:07.359 --> 00:09:08.760
not actually the data.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:10.719
This is helpful because,

00:09:10.719 --> 00:09:13.280
at least in the clinical trial world,

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:16.280
I would say we're working with medium-sized data,

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:18.359
not truly big data, but it is still helpful

00:09:18.359 --> 00:09:22.119
to not have to read in the whole data sets at the same time.

00:09:24.039 --> 00:09:25.039
Okay, so at this point,

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:28.559
you've structured your data product however you want.

00:09:28.559 --> 00:09:31.280
You've done a bunch of derivation code and added that.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:34.559
Now you get back to the version everything step.

00:09:34.559 --> 00:09:38.599
And so, Dapr will help you commit and push, essentially,

00:09:38.599 --> 00:09:42.479
all of your code and other versionable things

00:09:42.479 --> 00:09:43.520
to your GitHub repo.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:46.200
So, this is the derivation code

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:50.000
and all of the data product structuring logic.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.640
This is your RN files to track your package dependencies.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:56.159
And this is also all of the metadata

00:09:56.159 --> 00:09:58.200
around your input and output files.

00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:01.400
Okay, and then one final step,

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:03.679
which is that now you're ready to deploy it.

00:10:03.679 --> 00:10:04.960
So, at this point,

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:07.440
you can push your data product to the remote board,

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:10.760
and it's ready to share, to use for your own analysis,

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:14.559
to share with somebody else to use for their own analysis,

00:10:14.559 --> 00:10:15.960
and you're ready to go here.

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:21.599
There's actually a sixth step here,

00:10:21.599 --> 00:10:23.200
which is to iterate over this.

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:25.880
So, at this point, you can go back to step two,

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:27.239
add new input data,

00:10:28.119 --> 00:10:30.359
deploy a new version of the data product,

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.159
or you could add more derivation code,

00:10:32.159 --> 00:10:34.679
like maybe you have a new function you want to add,

00:10:34.679 --> 00:10:36.440
and then you can, for each of these,

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:38.039
you'd go back and go through the cycle

00:10:38.039 --> 00:10:40.520
and deploy a new version of the data product.

00:10:41.559 --> 00:10:44.440
The other helpful thing here is that all of this is version,

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:46.679
so if you have an analysis script

00:10:46.679 --> 00:10:48.320
that references the data product,

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:50.000
you can refer to it by version

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.919
so that it doesn't break when a new version is published.

00:10:53.919 --> 00:10:56.159
This is also where you can bring in collaborators

00:10:56.159 --> 00:10:59.000
to work on the data product with you.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:00.520
So, it doesn't have to be just you

00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:02.080
going through this iterative process.

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:05.000
You can bring in somebody else to do this as well.

00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:10.919
Just to show an example of how this might work,

00:11:10.919 --> 00:11:15.159
I'm showing a plot of data product collaboration over time

00:11:15.159 --> 00:11:16.520
in the form of commits

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:19.400
to selected data product repositories.

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:23.359
So, here, each line is an individual data product repo,

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:26.520
and then each dot is a commit to that repo,

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:27.960
and then the color of each dot

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:30.159
indicates a different collaborator identity.

00:11:31.919 --> 00:11:33.960
So, it's hard to tell exactly what's going on,

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:37.159
but I hope you can see that each of the data products

00:11:37.159 --> 00:11:39.359
has a different group of collaborators,

00:11:39.359 --> 00:11:42.359
and each of them have different bursts of activity over time.

00:11:44.159 --> 00:11:46.719
The other really cool thing is that some of these data

00:11:46.719 --> 00:11:49.719
products go back as far as 2022,

00:11:49.719 --> 00:11:52.640
which is quite exciting for me.

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:57.000
Some of these represent kind of scientific analysis questions

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.320
that have been persistent and interesting for many years,

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:03.280
and the data product has been useful

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:05.559
for those analyses for that whole time.

00:12:07.559 --> 00:12:09.280
So, I hope this shows, really,

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:12.119
how Dapr can be used as a collaborative framework.

00:12:13.919 --> 00:12:15.719
I do want to switch tracks a little bit now

00:12:15.719 --> 00:12:18.320
and perhaps address the elephant in the room,

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:20.960
which is, how do you actually get people to try this?

00:12:21.679 --> 00:12:24.320
So, I walked through, admittedly,

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:27.440
a number of different steps to create a data product,

00:12:28.039 --> 00:12:29.880
and for people trying this out,

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:31.719
they might need to learn to use new tools

00:12:31.719 --> 00:12:33.799
that they're not as comfortable with.

00:12:33.799 --> 00:12:35.840
So, how do you actually get people

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:37.599
onboarded to a framework like this?

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:40.520
So, I have a few tips here.

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:42.919
I will note that most of them are educational

00:12:42.919 --> 00:12:45.039
or focused on reducing barriers to entry.

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:48.159
We're not forcing anyone to use this framework.

00:12:49.599 --> 00:12:51.840
The first tip I have is to really provide

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:53.479
comprehensive training.

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:57.440
So, this might be hands-on demos with real data products.

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:00.320
I would say it's been very effective

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:02.359
to have one-on-one demos,

00:13:02.359 --> 00:13:04.159
so you can kind of look over somebody's shoulder

00:13:04.159 --> 00:13:05.919
and see when they run into issues.

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:09.320
We also have asynchronous learning materials,

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:13.000
so this is things like video tutorials, vignettes,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:14.919
and for all of these, just being really clear

00:13:14.919 --> 00:13:18.440
and providing dedicated debugging support,

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:20.880
that's really been helpful.

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:25.440
The second tip I have is to let people ease into the process.

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:29.039
So, you know, we do this by providing multiple DAPR roles.

00:13:29.039 --> 00:13:31.799
So, the first role is a reader role.

00:13:31.799 --> 00:13:35.200
So, at this point, people could essentially interact

00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:37.200
with the data product in read-only mode,

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:39.239
and they could use it for their analysis,

00:13:39.239 --> 00:13:42.039
but they don't have to fully learn the DAPR framework.

00:13:42.799 --> 00:13:44.640
They could then graduate to a writer role

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:47.000
where they would then learn the full suite

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:48.760
of DAPR packages and tools

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:50.840
and would contribute to derivation code.

00:13:51.799 --> 00:13:53.719
And then the third role is an owner.

00:13:53.719 --> 00:13:56.840
So, at this point, this is more of an admin role.

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:59.359
They would maybe manage access to the remote

00:13:59.359 --> 00:14:01.320
and do some provisioning activity,

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:03.960
and we don't have as many people getting fully to the owner role,

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:05.559
which is fine.

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:10.799
The third tip I have is really to show off the results,

00:14:10.799 --> 00:14:14.239
like show off what you can get by working within this framework.

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:18.039
It's not very convincing to show, for example,

00:14:18.039 --> 00:14:20.159
just the number of lines of derivation code

00:14:20.159 --> 00:14:21.359
you've added to a repo.

00:14:21.359 --> 00:14:23.159
That's not going to convince anyone.

00:14:23.679 --> 00:14:27.280
Instead, sharing things like maybe you have a Cordo report

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:28.799
that's linked to the data product

00:14:28.799 --> 00:14:32.479
that has key figures that get shown in stakeholder meetings,

00:14:32.479 --> 00:14:34.440
or maybe you have a Shiny app

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.640
that lets you explore the data product

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:39.640
and which derivations are involved in it.

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:44.440
And then finally, showing off the results of the collaboration.

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:45.599
So, if you find somebody

00:14:45.599 --> 00:14:48.119
who's not already a reproducibility nerd,

00:14:48.119 --> 00:14:52.000
but has tried out the framework and has had success with it,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.799
and then they can kind of champion the framework

00:14:54.799 --> 00:14:57.039
to other people, that's really key as well.

00:15:00.479 --> 00:15:02.359
So, despite all of these tips,

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:05.559
we do run into a lot of common roadblocks

00:15:05.559 --> 00:15:07.679
getting people onboarded to this framework.

00:15:07.679 --> 00:15:09.520
And I think a lot of these will be familiar

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:10.760
to many folks here as well.

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:12.880
They're not specific to Dapr.

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:14.119
And so, I just wanted to walk through

00:15:14.159 --> 00:15:15.960
how we approach some of these.

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:19.440
So, the first common roadblock

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:22.599
is that managing credentials is annoying.

00:15:22.599 --> 00:15:25.520
So, you know, maybe you have like a Git token,

00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:27.760
maybe you have like S3 keys,

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:30.400
maybe you have another data platform credential

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:31.679
you need to provide.

00:15:31.679 --> 00:15:34.719
And all of these probably expire at a different time,

00:15:34.719 --> 00:15:37.200
which, you know, you can never really control that.

00:15:37.919 --> 00:15:40.440
We've had good success using the keyring package

00:15:40.440 --> 00:15:41.960
to manage all types of credentials,

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:43.919
but there's a lot of different

00:15:43.919 --> 00:15:45.919
credential management packages out there.

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:50.640
The second common roadblock is focused on

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:52.840
how do you really impart Git best practices?

00:15:54.479 --> 00:15:56.400
I will also say there's a lot of resources out here

00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:58.280
for getting started with Git.

00:15:58.280 --> 00:16:01.919
I just wanted to shout out Jenny Bryan's Happy Git with R,

00:16:01.919 --> 00:16:03.520
which is an excellent resource.

00:16:04.599 --> 00:16:06.520
But I think the thing I want to focus on here

00:16:06.520 --> 00:16:08.840
is that we've all been at the learning stage

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:11.719
for, you know, learning how to use Git and GitHub.

00:16:11.719 --> 00:16:13.799
We've all accidentally created a merge conflict

00:16:13.799 --> 00:16:15.919
or committed a file that we shouldn't.

00:16:15.919 --> 00:16:17.280
And so, I think for all of these,

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:19.880
you know, leading with solutions when you're teaching people

00:16:19.880 --> 00:16:21.400
how to work through these issues,

00:16:21.400 --> 00:16:24.280
that's really key because we were all learning this once.

00:16:25.520 --> 00:16:27.479
And then the third common roadblock

00:16:27.479 --> 00:16:30.880
kind of relates to the corporate enterprise environment.

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:32.440
So, maybe you have a corporate firewall

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:36.559
or maybe you have to configure your internal package manager

00:16:36.559 --> 00:16:38.280
to install packages.

00:16:38.280 --> 00:16:40.640
And for these, I would say it's been most helpful

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:43.760
just to provide example setup code,

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:46.960
especially across different operating systems.

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:48.479
And I would say the key point

00:16:48.479 --> 00:16:50.200
for walking through these common roadblocks

00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:52.320
is that they will happen,

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:54.200
and the goal is really to try to empower people

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:55.840
to be able to work through them

00:16:55.840 --> 00:16:57.239
when they encounter them the next time.

00:16:57.239 --> 00:16:59.479
So, that's really what we try to focus on

00:16:59.479 --> 00:17:02.000
when we have people come to us with these issues.

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:07.079
So, I'd just like to end with some Dapr resources.

00:17:07.079 --> 00:17:09.400
So, if you're interested in trying this out,

00:17:09.439 --> 00:17:12.079
Dapr is available on GitHub.

00:17:12.079 --> 00:17:15.640
I will note that despite having some data products

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:19.079
that are over three years old, Dapr is still maturing.

00:17:19.079 --> 00:17:22.719
It also only supports RDS and QS file types,

00:17:22.719 --> 00:17:25.520
but we are thinking about some parquet development.

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:28.839
It also only supports three different types of remote boards.

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:31.520
And then the final thought that I'll leave you with

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:35.199
is what I said about trying to make your analysis pipelines

00:17:35.199 --> 00:17:37.839
more reproducible resonated with you.

00:17:37.839 --> 00:17:38.839
If you're trying to get away

00:17:38.839 --> 00:17:41.239
from some of the disposable data work,

00:17:41.239 --> 00:17:43.800
but maybe you're not fully ready to take the plunge

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:46.079
into the type two world of Dapr,

00:17:46.079 --> 00:17:47.800
I would encourage you to try out

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:49.719
some of the tools that Dapr uses.

00:17:49.719 --> 00:17:52.040
So, try out renv, pins, targets.

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:54.599
These are all wonderful packages

00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:57.359
for making your pipelines more reproducible.

00:17:59.319 --> 00:18:01.319
With that, I just need to acknowledge

00:18:01.319 --> 00:18:03.439
the other members of the Dapr dev team.

00:18:03.439 --> 00:18:06.359
So, big thanks to Afshin Mashadi-Hussain,

00:18:06.359 --> 00:18:08.319
who was the original developer and creator

00:18:08.319 --> 00:18:10.479
of the Dapr suite of packages.

00:18:10.479 --> 00:18:12.959
And then thanks to Leslie, Barack, and Mandeep,

00:18:12.959 --> 00:18:15.319
